## Key Distinction

Most systems:

👉 govern behavior after state exists  

The Millings Method™:

👉 governs what is allowed to become state  
👉 and ensures that state remains valid over time  

---

## Shared Admissibility Infrastructure (SAI)

SAI is a cross-system layer that maintains a shared reference for admissible signal.

It ensures:

- consistent signal interpretation across systems  
- state alignment between distributed environments  
- execution grounded in shared reality  

Without SAI:

👉 systems remain internally coherent  
👉 but diverge from each other over time  

---

## Signal Admissibility Layer (SAL)

SAL governs what is allowed to enter a system as signal.

It includes:

- identity resolution  
- domain separation  
- provenance validation  
- collision detection (HFI protocol)  
- quarantine of unverifiable inputs  

---

👉 SAL prevents mis-specified signal from becoming state.

---

## System Integrity Chain

Admissibility is not a checkpoint.

It is a continuous constraint across:

- signal  
- state  
- execution  
- feedback  
- reality alignment  

---

👉 If any layer breaks, the system drifts.

